data.content:
## What happened

C# 14 introduces new implicit span conversions. When you call `.Contains()` on an `int[]`, overload resolution now picks **`MemoryExtensions.Contains(ReadOnlySpan<T>, T)`** instead of `Enumerable.Contains<T>(IEnumerable<T>, T)`. Span-based methods **cannot be represented in expression trees**, so the compiled/interpreted expression throws at runtime.

## How to fix

Force the `Enumerable.Contains` overload by casting to `IEnumerable<int>` or using `.AsEnumerable()`:

```csharp
// Option 1: .AsEnumerable()
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => array.AsEnumerable().Contains(num);

// Option 2: explicit static call
Expression<Func<int[], int, bool>> expr =
    (array, num) => Enumerable.Contains(array, num);
```

Both approaches prevent the compiler from choosing the span overload, keeping the expression tree valid.
